---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import GovernanceDiagram from '../components/GovernanceDiagram.astro';
import { externalLinks } from '../config';
---

<Layout title="About">
  {/* ── Hero ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="mb-16">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-4">About</p>
    <h1 class="max-w-4xl mb-6">The international standard for written language conversion systems.</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-ink-muted max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
      ISO 24229 gives every system that converts text from one script or spelling to another — transliteration, transcription, romanisation, and orthographic reform alike — a single, unambiguous identifier. This website is the official register, operated by CalConnect as Registration Authority, designated by ISO.
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* ── Purpose ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="rule-section">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Purpose</p>
    <h2 class="max-w-2xl mb-6">Why this standard exists.</h2>
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        A number of international applications require the identification of written language conversion systems — terminology, lexicography, bibliography, and linguistics, especially for reverse transliteration, computational linguistics, and machine pronunciation.
      </p>
      <p>
        The term <em>written language conversion</em> is intended to refer to all types of transformations of written texts from one spelling system to another. It includes both script conversion (change of script: transliteration, transcription) and conversion of texts without changing the script (e.g. transcription of foreign names or words using the alphabet of a target language, change of the orthography in a language).
      </p>
      <p>
        ISO 24229 is one of three important ISO standards for internationalisation, alongside the <a href={externalLinks.iso639Standard} class="underline">ISO 639</a> series (language codes) and <a href={externalLinks.iso15924Standard} class="underline">ISO 15924</a> (script codes). Together, they let any written form of any language be identified unambiguously.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Scope ──────────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="rule-section">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Scope</p>
    <h2 class="max-w-2xl mb-6">What the standard defines.</h2>
    <ul class="max-w-2xl space-y-3 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Conversion system codes — structured identifiers for written language conversion systems</li>
      <li>Spelling system codes — identifiers for the source and target forms being converted</li>
      <li>Conversion system authorities — identifiers for the bodies that manage conversion systems</li>
      <li>Requirements and processes for registering codes and authorities</li>
      <li>Data models for the codes and the metadata associated with them</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  {/* ── Governance ─────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="rule-section">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">Governance</p>
    <h2 class="max-w-2xl mb-6">How the register is managed.</h2>
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed mb-8">
      <p>
        <a href={externalLinks.calconnect} class="underline">CalConnect</a> is the Registration Authority (ISO 24229/RA), designated by ISO. The register is operated by <a href={externalLinks.ribose} class="underline">Ribose</a>. An Advisory Group (ISO 24229/AG) of 4–12 experts — including a representative of ISO/TC 46 — reviews submissions at its bimonthly meeting. As a rule, decisions are made by consensus; if a vote is needed, a decision is approved when more than two-thirds of members vote for it.
      </p>
    </div>
    <GovernanceDiagram />
    <p class="mt-6 text-sm">
      <a href="/specification/governance" class="text-ink-muted hover:text-gold-deep dark:hover:text-gold-bright">Full governance and lifecycle →</a>
    </p>
  </section>

  {/* ── Logo + philosophy ──────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="rule-section">
    <div class="flex flex-col md:flex-row items-start gap-12 mb-10">
      <img
        src="/assets/logos/iso-24229-logo.svg"
        alt="ISO 24229 logomark"
        width="160"
        height="160"
        class="shrink-0 w-28 md:w-40 h-auto"
      />
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The logomark</p>
        <h2 class="max-w-xl">An atlas of refraction.</h2>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-6 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        At the centre of the ISO 24229 logomark sits a circle divided into two halves. This is the semantic core — the invariant meaning that exists before any script is chosen, before any pen meets paper. Meaning, in its essence, does not change when it crosses from one writing system to another. The concept of <em>water</em> is the same whether written <span class="font-mono">水</span> in Hanzi, <span class="font-mono">мөрөн</span> in Cyrillic, or <span class="font-mono">usma</span> in Latin. The two halves of the core acknowledge that meaning is always dual: it lives both in the intention of the writer and in the comprehension of the reader, and these two are never quite identical.
      </p>
      <p>
        Around this core, two concentric circles trace the periphery of expression. These are the writing systems — the scripts, orthographies, and conventions that give visible form to meaning. The inner ring is the source: the system from which a conversion begins. The outer ring is the target: the system into which meaning is refracted. Between them lies the act of conversion itself, the space where ISO 24229 operates.
      </p>
      <p>
        Both the semantic centre and the expressive rings are set at an angle — a rotation governed by the golden ratio. This is not decoration. It is the logomark's deepest statement: meaning and its written expression are never perfectly aligned. They drift. The angle between them is the inherent bias of every transliteration, every transcription, every romanisation. When Arabic flows into Latin, when Cyrillic flows into Latin, when Hanzi flows into Pinyin, something is preserved and something is refracted — bent slightly, like light passing through water.
      </p>
      <p>
        ISO 24229 exists to make this refraction <strong>visible</strong>. Every code in the register is a named, identifiable conversion path. By assigning each system a unique code, the standard transforms an otherwise opaque transformation into an auditable, citable act. The register does not eliminate drift — that is impossible — but it makes drift <em>transparent</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The concentric rings acknowledge that expression is layered, that conversion is never lossless, and that the path from meaning to written form is always mediated. The golden ratio — nature's proportion of growth and harmony — suggests that this mediation is not a defect to be corrected but a natural property of written language, as fundamental as the angle of sunlight through a prism.
      </p>
      <p>
        The ISO 24229 register is, in this sense, an atlas of refraction: a comprehensive, maintained catalogue of the known ways that meaning bends as it passes from one script to another. By naming each path, we shed light on the original authentic meaning — not by freezing it in a single form, but by making every transformation traceable.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {/* ── Colours ──────────────────────────────────────────────── */}
  <section class="rule-section">
    <p class="eyebrow mb-3">The colours</p>
    <h2 class="max-w-2xl mb-6">Gold and blue, held in tension.</h2>
    <div class="max-w-2xl space-y-5 text-ink-muted leading-relaxed">
      <p>
        The logomark's palette is drawn from two opposing forces. <strong>Gold</strong> — warm, luminous, the colour of things held precious — marks the semantic core. It is the colour of meaning itself: invariant, valuable, the thing that persists across conversion. <strong>Blue</strong> — cool, structural, the colour of systems and rules — marks the concentric rings of expression. It is the colour of the written form: engineered, conventional, subject to reform.
      </p>
      <p>
        Where gold and blue meet, at the angle of the golden ratio, the two colours do not merge into green. They hold their distinction. This is intentional: meaning and expression are not the same thing, and ISO 24229's purpose is to keep them legibly separate — to ensure that every reader can tell which is which, even when they are tightly interleaved.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
